1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,040
I'm dismissed to Children's Church this time.

2
00:00:03,020 --> 00:00:04,800
Is it fun having Will and Kathy call back?

3
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:10,800
Thanks for being here.

4
00:00:15,790 --> 00:00:18,790
Pastor Dave tells me that we've just gone high-tech in a different way,

5
00:00:20,250 --> 00:00:24,130
that now the text from the messages are on the website.

6
00:00:24,730 --> 00:00:29,170
So starting tomorrow, you can get today's message in text form.

7
00:00:30,180 --> 00:00:32,200
You can also get it on CD, and you can get it on tape.

8
00:00:32,280 --> 00:00:34,040
So we're getting out there, you know?

9
00:00:34,160 --> 00:00:35,980
That's exciting, so I appreciate those guys.

10
00:00:36,360 --> 00:00:39,180
We've also had a massive hardware failure this morning.

11
00:00:39,180 --> 00:00:47,060
We had a little trouble in this service, but I just thank God for the team who are so committed to sweating bullets back there while we're all just worshiping the Lord.

12
00:00:47,660 --> 00:00:50,960
I mean, they're writing me signs saying good, you know, and all this stuff.

13
00:00:51,240 --> 00:00:54,360
And I want to give them a thanks for all that you guys do.

14
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:04,160
Well, this morning we are in the fourth installment in a series.

15
00:01:04,340 --> 00:01:05,440
And can you indulge me?

16
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:06,680
Can I roll my sleeves up a little bit?

17
00:01:06,680 --> 00:01:07,700
I can't preach like this.

18
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:08,260
Can I do that?

19
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:11,200
This just feels too stuck, you know.

20
00:01:12,860 --> 00:01:13,420
Take the talk.

21
00:01:13,480 --> 00:01:13,960
Can we do that?

22
00:01:13,960 --> 00:01:14,240
Okay.

23
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:22,660
Okay. All right. All right. Now, we can really get... I'll stop right there, though. That's

24
00:01:22,660 --> 00:01:32,050
going to be all right. But here's the... I can't preach all bundled up. You know, given

25
00:01:32,050 --> 00:01:36,910
the tragedy that has happened and that we're actually experiencing even this morning, I

26
00:01:36,910 --> 00:01:42,030
think we're very sensitive to death. We're sensitive to destruction. We are sensitive

27
00:01:42,030 --> 00:01:46,850
to carnage. And, you know, we're face-to-face with these things in ways that we have not

28
00:01:46,850 --> 00:01:53,690
experienced in a while. One of the challenges to the Christian faith is that if you take

29
00:01:53,690 --> 00:02:01,930
a look at the Old Testament, it is just full of death, destruction, and carnage. And in

30
00:02:01,930 --> 00:02:06,890
today's world, our sensibilities, especially in America, where we are really removed from

31
00:02:06,890 --> 00:02:14,160
these events by and large, that we just feel like, what kind of a God is this that sort

32
00:02:14,160 --> 00:02:20,490
of is behind all of this to begin with. In fact, I've heard it said in different ways

33
00:02:20,490 --> 00:02:26,810
that, you know, God is kind of a schizophrenic God. Because in one sense, there's all this

34
00:02:26,810 --> 00:02:31,110
death and destruction and all of that. And then all of a sudden, we're talking about

35
00:02:31,110 --> 00:02:39,630
him being loving and merciful. Well, which is he? How do you bring those two tensions

36
00:02:39,630 --> 00:02:43,950
together? In fact, it's been so well laid out in this book that we're studying, Lee

37
00:02:43,950 --> 00:02:50,110
Strobel's The Case for Faith. We're in the fourth chapter here. Robert A. Wilson, in the first part

38
00:02:50,110 --> 00:02:55,790
of the chapter for the day, says, the Bible tells us to be like God, and then on page after page,

39
00:02:55,790 --> 00:03:02,710
it describes God as a mass murderer. That's an interesting charge leveled at God, isn't it?

40
00:03:03,880 --> 00:03:06,920
Now, King David, and we're going to talk more about him in this message later,

41
00:03:07,300 --> 00:03:12,580
says in Psalm 86, but you, O Lord, are a compassionate and a gracious God,

42
00:03:13,260 --> 00:03:16,320
slow to anger, abounding in love and faithfulness.

43
00:03:18,590 --> 00:03:19,510
Well, which is it?

44
00:03:21,480 --> 00:03:23,240
And I suspect that many of you,

45
00:03:23,300 --> 00:03:25,400
whether you've been believers for a long time

46
00:03:25,400 --> 00:03:26,820
or fairly new to Christianity,

47
00:03:27,220 --> 00:03:29,740
you may have run across this question in different forms

48
00:03:29,740 --> 00:03:31,880
and said, yeah, what about that?

49
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:34,740
Some of the Old Testament,

50
00:03:34,880 --> 00:03:36,080
if you're reading it to your children,

51
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:38,680
you blush because there are some scenes in there

52
00:03:38,680 --> 00:03:41,880
that you really don't want to read as a bedtime story.

53
00:03:44,060 --> 00:03:46,020
It's interesting how we've got these little children's Bibles.

54
00:03:46,020 --> 00:03:48,760
they really sanitize a lot of the Old Testament stories

55
00:03:48,760 --> 00:03:53,400
because they really are something that would be PG-13 or R-rated if it was in the theater.

56
00:03:55,700 --> 00:03:57,500
How do you reconcile those two positions?

57
00:03:59,370 --> 00:04:02,110
The challenge is, it's put out there, is that you really can't.

58
00:04:04,060 --> 00:04:08,280
And so what's really at stake here is the very character of God himself.

59
00:04:09,220 --> 00:04:12,500
Is he consistent or do we have two different gods represented

60
00:04:12,500 --> 00:04:15,820
or is the Bible basically just full of malarkey

61
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:19,700
because it can't make up its mind, you know, where is God and so forth.

62
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:25,580
Let me give you some examples here.

63
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:26,520
Genesis 19.

64
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:33,220
Then the Lord rained down fire and burning sulfur from the heavens on Sodom and Gomorrah.

65
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:37,240
He utterly destroyed them along with the other cities and villages of the plain,

66
00:04:37,560 --> 00:04:41,500
eliminating all life, people, plants, and animals alike.

67
00:04:44,850 --> 00:04:47,370
Deuteronomy chapter 7, a few books later.

68
00:04:47,730 --> 00:04:51,250
When the Lord your God brings you into the land you're about to enter and occupy,

69
00:04:51,250 --> 00:04:53,970
he will clear away many nations ahead of you.

70
00:04:54,510 --> 00:04:59,110
The Hittites, Girgashites, Amorites, Canaanites, Perizzites, Hittites, and the Jebusites.

71
00:04:59,570 --> 00:05:02,570
These seven nations all are more powerful than you

72
00:05:02,570 --> 00:05:06,330
when the Lord your God hands these nations over to you and conquers them.

73
00:05:06,510 --> 00:05:11,590
You must completely destroy them, make no treaties with them, and show them no mercy.

74
00:05:13,950 --> 00:05:15,250
That is strong language.

75
00:05:16,620 --> 00:05:18,980
That was a violent scene we were describing there.

76
00:05:19,680 --> 00:05:21,160
What do we make of stories like that?

77
00:05:22,210 --> 00:05:24,810
Well, in 1794, Thomas Paine wrote,

78
00:05:25,290 --> 00:05:26,930
in The Age of Reason, he wrote this.

79
00:05:26,950 --> 00:05:27,790
This is his response.

80
00:05:28,740 --> 00:05:30,960
Whenever we read these obscene stories,

81
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:32,720
the voluptuous debaucheries,

82
00:05:33,220 --> 00:05:35,480
the cruel and torturous executions,

83
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:37,080
the unrelenting vindictiveness

84
00:05:37,080 --> 00:05:39,620
with which more than half the Bible is filled,

85
00:05:39,940 --> 00:05:41,720
it would be more consistent that we call it

86
00:05:41,720 --> 00:05:44,020
the work of a demon than the word of God.

87
00:05:47,430 --> 00:05:48,470
We know where he stands.

88
00:05:50,390 --> 00:05:51,210
What do you think about that?

89
00:05:52,290 --> 00:05:53,070
Have you ever wondered that?

90
00:05:54,470 --> 00:05:56,110
How do we put together all these stories?

91
00:05:56,710 --> 00:05:58,870
How do we reconcile the New Testament picture

92
00:05:58,870 --> 00:06:01,060
and the Old Testament picture

93
00:06:01,060 --> 00:06:04,080
as being of the same God in the same book?

94
00:06:06,550 --> 00:06:07,570
Well, there's one way to do it.

95
00:06:07,590 --> 00:06:08,990
You simply reject the Bible.

96
00:06:09,510 --> 00:06:11,270
You reject the God of both Testaments,

97
00:06:11,370 --> 00:06:14,610
and you say this is just a bunch of interesting narrative

98
00:06:14,610 --> 00:06:17,010
from some backwater places

99
00:06:17,010 --> 00:06:19,530
with people who are unenlightened and so forth,

100
00:06:19,530 --> 00:06:21,990
and they love writing about bloody stuff,

101
00:06:22,130 --> 00:06:23,930
and we just ignore the whole thing.

102
00:06:24,840 --> 00:06:25,660
It's one way to do it.

103
00:06:25,980 --> 00:06:32,040
You just say it's myth, it's ancient narrative and story and it's bloody and those people

104
00:06:32,040 --> 00:06:37,720
were not sophisticated and we just let it all go and reject the God of the Bible and

105
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:38,460
the Bible itself.

106
00:06:39,860 --> 00:06:43,920
Now underneath this issue, as I've just kind of hinted at it, is rejecting the Bible itself

107
00:06:43,920 --> 00:06:48,280
because see underneath this tension with the character of God is also if we're going to

108
00:06:48,280 --> 00:06:55,790
use the Bible to talk about God at all, whether you're a critic or a fan of God, you're still

109
00:06:55,790 --> 00:07:02,170
using this book, can you really do that with intellectual integrity? Does this book have

110
00:07:02,170 --> 00:07:07,050
any reliability to describe anything about God at all? How do we know this thing is true

111
00:07:07,050 --> 00:07:10,670
is really what the question is. So we're going to really look at two different issues this

112
00:07:10,670 --> 00:07:15,460
morning. We're going to look at the character of God and also the reliability of the Bible

113
00:07:15,460 --> 00:07:21,420
itself. Now one thing I want you to kind of keep in the back of your mind is just because

114
00:07:21,420 --> 00:07:26,980
the Bible will describe a scenario or an event or something that people do or commit

115
00:07:26,980 --> 00:07:33,300
against one another, it doesn't mean the Bible necessarily condones the behavior. It simply

116
00:07:33,300 --> 00:07:40,400
records it. And there's a big difference between recording something and writing it down as

117
00:07:40,400 --> 00:07:46,280
if this is the way to be. There are a number of horrible events in here that people did

118
00:07:46,280 --> 00:07:51,920
to one another that is simply written down as history and as narrative. But God is not

119
00:07:51,920 --> 00:07:56,080
condoning that behavior. So I want us to be careful when we're looking at this that we're

120
00:07:56,080 --> 00:08:05,020
not confusing those two issues. Okay. In the book, The Case for Faith, Lee Strobel, the

121
00:08:05,020 --> 00:08:13,380
author, trained as a journalist, asks Dr. Norman Geisler a really summary statement

122
00:08:13,380 --> 00:08:19,130
question. He says, isn't there a big difference between the oft-cruel God of the Old Testament

123
00:08:19,130 --> 00:08:27,540
and the loving God of the New Testament? And that's our tension this morning. And Dr. Geisler

124
00:08:27,540 --> 00:08:33,170
responds with an interesting statement. He says, when you do a word study and you do

125
00:08:33,170 --> 00:08:40,050
a word count of the word mercy, and he uses the King James for whatever reason, he finds

126
00:08:40,050 --> 00:08:45,190
out how many times does the word mercy happen in the King James Bible. King James translation

127
00:08:45,190 --> 00:08:49,490
is an older translation, kind of a standard. And he says when you run the numbers, there

128
00:08:49,490 --> 00:08:57,850
are 261 occurrences of the word mercy in the King James Bible. And 72% of those references

129
00:08:57,850 --> 00:08:59,390
are in the Old Testament.

130
00:09:01,070 --> 00:09:03,710
It's a three-to-one ratio of the concept

131
00:09:03,710 --> 00:09:05,370
and the discussion of mercy

132
00:09:05,370 --> 00:09:07,310
in the Old Testament to the New.

133
00:09:07,550 --> 00:09:08,090
Isn't that interesting?

134
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:10,520
Because we don't simply think of it that way.

135
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:14,000
You'd think, big bad God of the Old Testament,

136
00:09:14,460 --> 00:09:16,160
loving, merciful God of the New Testament,

137
00:09:16,600 --> 00:09:19,380
but mercy is talked about 72% of the time

138
00:09:19,380 --> 00:09:20,960
in the Old Testament.

139
00:09:22,840 --> 00:09:25,240
The word love is also run through those same numbers,

140
00:09:25,240 --> 00:09:28,520
and it shows up 322 times in the King James Version,

141
00:09:28,520 --> 00:09:31,860
and he finds that about 50% is in each testament.

142
00:09:32,760 --> 00:09:37,320
So love and mercy is running throughout both sides of the Bible.

143
00:09:38,770 --> 00:09:41,430
Now, I want to keep him honest, and so I ran the numbers myself.

144
00:09:41,930 --> 00:09:44,210
I went to my Bible software, and I typed in these words,

145
00:09:44,290 --> 00:09:46,010
and I just ran it and see how many times it shows up,

146
00:09:46,330 --> 00:09:48,970
counted them up, and sure enough, these numbers are accurate.

147
00:09:51,780 --> 00:09:53,480
Dr. Geisler goes on to make another argument

148
00:09:53,480 --> 00:09:55,520
that I think is really interesting that I didn't even realize.

149
00:09:55,980 --> 00:09:57,620
He says, you know, the argument could be made

150
00:09:57,620 --> 00:09:59,540
that the God of the New Testament

151
00:09:59,540 --> 00:10:01,660
is actually more judgmental

152
00:10:01,660 --> 00:10:04,400
than the reference to God in the Old Testament

153
00:10:04,400 --> 00:10:06,120
because in the New Testament,

154
00:10:06,120 --> 00:10:10,750
we talk a lot about heaven and hell

155
00:10:10,750 --> 00:10:12,870
and about future judgment forever.

156
00:10:14,230 --> 00:10:15,790
The Old Testament doesn't talk about that.

157
00:10:17,390 --> 00:10:18,150
In the Old Testament,

158
00:10:18,270 --> 00:10:20,810
judgment comes as a city is occupied,

159
00:10:21,050 --> 00:10:22,510
as people take over the land,

160
00:10:22,690 --> 00:10:24,030
but nowhere do you talk about

161
00:10:24,030 --> 00:10:25,830
eternal judgment anywhere.

162
00:10:26,510 --> 00:10:27,950
That's a New Testament concept,

163
00:10:28,170 --> 00:10:29,130
and it could be argued

164
00:10:29,130 --> 00:10:32,650
that so much of the New Testament is about eternal judgment

165
00:10:32,650 --> 00:10:35,770
that the New Testament is actually more judgmental than the old.

166
00:10:36,740 --> 00:10:37,920
That's an interesting argument, isn't it?

167
00:10:38,200 --> 00:10:39,340
I'd never thought of it that way.

168
00:10:40,300 --> 00:10:43,340
But just looking at those concepts, I can see that to be true.

169
00:10:43,640 --> 00:10:46,660
At the same time, there is a consistency in the Scripture.

170
00:10:47,300 --> 00:10:50,040
The Bible says in Malachi 3.6,

171
00:10:50,040 --> 00:10:53,410
I am the Lord, and I do not change.

172
00:10:56,880 --> 00:10:59,320
What we're really seeing, if you do careful study,

173
00:11:00,200 --> 00:11:01,900
instead of just letting a friend say,

174
00:11:01,900 --> 00:11:04,440
you know I opened up this and I read this awful story

175
00:11:04,440 --> 00:11:06,320
and just that God of the Old Testament

176
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:08,400
I don't want to believe in him, I don't like him

177
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:10,440
I don't want to go there, this Bible

178
00:11:10,440 --> 00:11:12,500
is ridiculous, I don't want anything

179
00:11:12,500 --> 00:11:14,360
to do with your faith, we need to push them

180
00:11:14,360 --> 00:11:16,420
back to really study and look at those

181
00:11:16,420 --> 00:11:18,180
documents in context

182
00:11:18,180 --> 00:11:20,780
and you realize there's a consistency

183
00:11:20,780 --> 00:11:22,060
throughout the Old Testament

184
00:11:22,060 --> 00:11:24,320
and the New Testament about God's

185
00:11:24,320 --> 00:11:25,840
judgment and about his mercy

186
00:11:25,840 --> 00:11:28,240
that they're intertwined

187
00:11:28,240 --> 00:11:30,600
and they run throughout the entire Bible

188
00:11:30,600 --> 00:11:35,290
but still

189
00:11:35,290 --> 00:11:39,110
The charge could be leveled at you, but you know, word studies aside, that's all fine.

190
00:11:40,080 --> 00:11:43,180
But there are just some really difficult passages, like this one.

191
00:11:43,680 --> 00:11:45,520
This comes out of Exodus chapter 12.

192
00:11:45,640 --> 00:11:48,640
This is coming out of right after all the plagues of Egypt,

193
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:53,000
and the Pharaoh's not going to let the people go.

194
00:11:54,080 --> 00:11:59,520
And over and over and over, they've ramped up the intensity of the plagues upon Egypt,

195
00:12:00,350 --> 00:12:02,350
and finally this scenario happens.

196
00:12:02,850 --> 00:12:05,280
And Moses called for the leaders of Israel and said,

197
00:12:05,280 --> 00:12:09,420
Tell each of your families to slaughter the lamb they have set apart for the Passover.

198
00:12:09,860 --> 00:12:11,400
Drain each lamb's blood into a basin.

199
00:12:11,520 --> 00:12:14,980
Then take a cluster of hyssop branches and dip it into the lamb's blood.

200
00:12:15,180 --> 00:12:20,380
Then strike the hyssop against the top and the sides of the door frame, staining it with blood.

201
00:12:20,920 --> 00:12:23,880
And remember, no one is allowed to leave the house until morning.

202
00:12:24,140 --> 00:12:28,100
For the Lord will pass through the land and strike down the Egyptians.

203
00:12:28,460 --> 00:12:31,920
But when he sees the blood on the top and the sides of the door frame,

204
00:12:32,120 --> 00:12:34,500
the Lord will pass over your home.

205
00:12:35,570 --> 00:12:39,190
He will not permit the destroyer to enter and strike down your firstborn.

206
00:12:39,610 --> 00:12:41,190
A few verses later,

207
00:12:41,970 --> 00:12:45,750
And at midnight the Lord killed all the firstborn sons in the land of Egypt,

208
00:12:45,750 --> 00:12:48,210
and the firstborn son of Pharaoh who sat on the throne,

209
00:12:48,550 --> 00:12:50,730
to the firstborn son of the captive in the dungeon.

210
00:12:51,150 --> 00:12:53,710
And even the firstborn of their livestock were killed.

211
00:12:54,230 --> 00:12:57,410
Pharaoh and his officials and all the people of Egypt woke up during the night,

212
00:12:57,490 --> 00:12:59,710
and loud wailing was heard throughout the land of Egypt.

213
00:12:59,970 --> 00:13:02,950
There was not a single house where someone had not died.

214
00:13:04,020 --> 00:13:05,160
What do you make of that narrative?

215
00:13:06,500 --> 00:13:10,080
violent, horrible scenario.

216
00:13:10,730 --> 00:13:12,870
And that experience is foundational

217
00:13:12,870 --> 00:13:15,010
to the Jewish celebration of the Passover,

218
00:13:15,630 --> 00:13:17,910
where God passed over the homes

219
00:13:17,910 --> 00:13:19,770
that had the blood that were the Jews

220
00:13:19,770 --> 00:13:22,080
that were being saved.

221
00:13:23,790 --> 00:13:25,330
What about this, Jonah chapter 1?

222
00:13:25,510 --> 00:13:27,710
The Lord gave this message to Jonah,

223
00:13:27,810 --> 00:13:28,670
the son of Amittai,

224
00:13:28,790 --> 00:13:30,810
get up and go to the great city of Nineveh,

225
00:13:31,170 --> 00:13:32,850
announce my judgment against it,

226
00:13:33,270 --> 00:13:36,410
because I have seen how wicked its people are.

227
00:13:37,600 --> 00:13:39,460
The question kind of boils down to this.

228
00:13:39,920 --> 00:13:45,210
How do we worship a God who murders innocent people?

229
00:13:46,420 --> 00:13:50,400
How do we worship a God that allows children to be slaughtered?

230
00:13:51,630 --> 00:13:55,690
And that's really a deep emotional issue underneath these challenges.

231
00:13:56,680 --> 00:14:00,000
And I think we have to come back and step back and say, let's look at this again.

232
00:14:00,360 --> 00:14:04,920
We need to face, first of all, the issue of the holiness of God.

233
00:14:06,720 --> 00:14:09,960
In our very sanitized world, it's easy to miss this concept.

234
00:14:09,960 --> 00:14:16,910
The reality is this, God is holy, God is separate, God is perfect, God is pure.

235
00:14:17,530 --> 00:14:21,990
God is something that's very hard for us to conceptualize coming from our very broken position.

236
00:14:25,380 --> 00:14:30,740
When we violate God's plan, when we go our own way, when we seek meaning in life apart from God,

237
00:14:30,940 --> 00:14:35,860
we break his commands, we violate that divine sense of right and wrong in the universe,

238
